-- ============================================================
-- Quiz Seed: 2 Samuel Chapters 21–24
-- Target table: chapter_quizzes
-- Difficulties: kids (3 Qs), teens (5 Qs), adults (8 Qs) = 16 per chapter
-- Total: 4 chapters × 16 = 64 questions
-- correct_answer is always 'a'
-- ============================================================

-- ═══ 2 Samuel Chapter 21 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('2 Samuel', 21, 'kids', 1, 'Why was there a famine for three years in Israel?', 'Because Saul and his house had killed the Gibeonites, breaking a covenant Israel had made with them', 'Because the people had worshipped idols', 'Because there was no rain for three years', 'Because David had sinned in the matter of Bathsheba', 'a', 'David sought the face of the LORD, and the LORD answered, "It is for Saul, and for his bloody house, because he slew the Gibeonites" (2 Samuel 21:1).'),
('2 Samuel', 21, 'kids', 2, 'Who watched over the bodies of Saul''s sons on the hill, keeping the birds and beasts away?', 'Rizpah, the daughter of Aiah, Saul''s concubine', 'Bathsheba the queen', 'The priests of the LORD', 'Jonathan''s mother', 'a', 'Rizpah the daughter of Aiah took sackcloth, and spread it for her upon the rock, from the beginning of harvest until water dropped upon them out of heaven, and suffered neither the birds of the air to rest on them by day, nor the beasts of the field by night (2 Samuel 21:10).'),
('2 Samuel', 21, 'kids', 3, 'What happened to David when he was weary fighting a Philistine giant?', 'Abishai came and helped David and smote the Philistine and killed him', 'David''s sword broke but he escaped', 'Jonathan fought in David''s place', 'God blinded the giant and David escaped', 'a', 'Ishbi-benob thought to kill David; but Abishai the son of Zeruiah succoured David, and smote the Philistine, and killed him (2 Samuel 21:16-17).'),
-- Teens
('2 Samuel', 21, 'teens', 1, 'What did the Gibeonites ask of David to atone for Saul''s slaughter of them?', 'Let seven men of Saul''s sons be hanged up unto the LORD in Gibeah of Saul', 'A payment of silver and gold from the royal treasury', 'The rebuilding of the Gibeonite cities Saul had destroyed', 'The right to rule over the land of Benjamin', 'a', 'The Gibeonites said, "Let seven men of his sons be delivered unto us, and we will hang them up unto the LORD in Gibeah of Saul" (2 Samuel 21:6).'),
('2 Samuel', 21, 'teens', 2, 'Which of Saul''s descendants did David spare and why?', 'He spared Mephibosheth the son of Jonathan because of the LORD''s oath between David and Jonathan', 'He spared Michal because she was David''s wife', 'He spared Ish-bosheth''s son because he was the last heir', 'He spared Armoni because he had helped David during the flight from Saul', 'a', 'David spared Mephibosheth, the son of Jonathan the son of Saul, because of the LORD''s oath that was between them (2 Samuel 21:7).'),
('2 Samuel', 21, 'teens', 3, 'What did David do when he was told about Rizpah''s vigil over the bodies?', 'He gathered the bones of Saul and Jonathan from Jabesh-gilead and buried them with the bones of the hanged men in the sepulchre of Kish', 'He immediately ordered all the bodies buried in a royal tomb', 'He sent a military escort to guard Rizpah and the bodies', 'He went himself to Gibeah to mourn over the dead', 'a', 'David went and took the bones of Saul and the bones of Jonathan from the men of Jabesh-gilead, and gathered the bones of them that were hanged; they buried the bones of Saul and Jonathan in the country of Benjamin in the sepulchre of Kish (2 Samuel 21:12-14).'),
('2 Samuel', 21, 'teens', 4, 'What was the outcome of David''s men telling him he must not go out to battle anymore after he nearly died?', 'They said he must not quench the light of Israel, and thereafter the battles with the Philistines were fought by David''s mighty men', 'David agreed and appointed Joab as permanent commander in his place', 'David agreed to only direct battles from a tent in the rear', 'David refused and continued fighting personally despite their warning', 'a', 'David''s men sware unto him, saying, "Thou shalt go no more out with us to battle, that thou quench not the light of Israel" (2 Samuel 21:17). The subsequent giants were all slain by David''s servants (21:18-22).'),
('2 Samuel', 21, 'teens', 5, 'How many Philistine giants are recorded as falling in the battles described at the end of chapter 21?', 'Four, all of them fell at the hand of David and his servants', 'Seven', 'Three', 'Ten', 'a', 'These four were born to the giant in Gath, and fell by the hand of David, and by the hand of his servants (2 Samuel 21:22).'),
-- Adults
('2 Samuel', 21, 'adults', 1, 'What was the ancient covenant that Saul had broken regarding the Gibeonites, and how had Israel originally entered it?', 'Joshua had sworn to spare the Gibeonites who had deceived Israel; Saul violated this by seeking to slay them in his zeal for Israel and Judah', 'Moses had made a covenant with the Gibeonites at Sinai', 'David himself had personally promised Saul not to harm the Gibeonites', 'The covenant had been made by the elders of Israel at the time of the judges', 'a', 'The Gibeonites were not of the children of Israel, but of the remnant of the Amorites: and the children of Israel had sworn unto them; and Saul sought to slay them in his zeal (2 Samuel 21:2), referring to Joshua''s covenant in Joshua 9:15-19.'),
('2 Samuel', 21, 'adults', 2, 'During what period were the seven bodies exposed, and what natural sign marked the end of the judgment?', 'They were exposed at the beginning of barley harvest until water dropped upon them out of heaven, signaling the end of drought', 'They were exposed for forty days and nights during a great storm', 'They were exposed from Passover to the Feast of Tabernacles', 'They were exposed for a full year until a sign appeared in the heavens', 'a', 'Rizpah watched from the beginning of harvest until water dropped upon them out of heaven (2 Samuel 21:10), and God was intreated for the land after the bones of Saul, Jonathan, and the seven were buried (21:14).'),
('2 Samuel', 21, 'adults', 3, 'What was the weight of the spear of Ishbi-benob the Philistine giant who nearly killed David?', 'Three hundred shekels of brass', 'Five hundred shekels of iron', 'Two hundred shekels of iron', 'A talent of brass', 'a', 'Ishbi-benob...the weight of whose spear weighed three hundred shekels of brass in weight, he being girded with a new sword, thought to have slain David (2 Samuel 21:16).'),
('2 Samuel', 21, 'adults', 4, 'Who killed Lahmi the brother of Goliath, and what was distinctive about Lahmi''s weapon?', 'Elhanan the son of Jaare-oregim, a Bethlehemite, slew him; his spear staff was like a weaver''s beam', 'Abishai killed him with a sling and stone like David had killed Goliath', 'Joab killed him in a duel before the battle lines', 'Jonathan son of Shimeah killed him while on patrol near Gath', 'a', 'Elhanan the son of Jaare-oregim, a Bethlehemite, slew the brother of Goliath the Gittite, the staff of whose spear was like a weaver''s beam (2 Samuel 21:19).'),
('2 Samuel', 21, 'adults', 5, 'What was notable about the giant at Gath who had six fingers on each hand and six toes on each foot?', 'He had on every hand six fingers, and on every foot six toes, four and twenty in number, and he defied Israel; Jonathan the son of Shimeah slew him', 'He was the tallest man ever recorded in Israelite history', 'He wielded two swords simultaneously because of his extra digits', 'He had defeated three previous champions before Jonathan fought him', 'a', 'And yet again there was a battle in Gath, where was a man of great stature, that had on every hand six fingers, and on every foot six toes, four and twenty in number...and Jonathan the son of Shimeah the brother of David slew him (2 Samuel 21:20-21).'),
('2 Samuel', 21, 'adults', 6, 'What theological principle does the Gibeonite episode illustrate regarding covenant obligations?', 'That covenant oaths bind a nation across generations and that breaking them brings divine judgment, even when the original covenant was made by deception', 'That individual sins affect only the sinner and not future generations', 'That God judges only the generation that commits the sin', 'That political necessity can override covenant obligations', 'a', 'Though the Gibeonite covenant had been made by deception (Joshua 9), Israel was still bound by the oath sworn in the LORD''s name (Joshua 9:19); Saul''s violation brought famine on his entire nation (2 Samuel 21:1-2), demonstrating that covenant oaths have binding divine weight.'),
('2 Samuel', 21, 'adults', 7, 'What does Rizpah''s vigil over the exposed bodies communicate about maternal loyalty and its effect on David?', 'Her months-long vigil protecting the bodies moved David to give Saul and his house a proper burial, showing that courageous love can prompt justice from the powerful', 'Her vigil was a formal religious rite required by Mosaic law for atonement', 'Her action was considered shameful by the people of Israel', 'Her vigil had no effect on David and only ended with the rains', 'a', 'Rizpah kept her vigil from barley harvest until rain fell (2 Samuel 21:10), and when David was told what she had done, he was moved to gather and bury the bones of Saul, Jonathan, and the seven, and "after that God was intreated for the land" (21:14).'),
('2 Samuel', 21, 'adults', 8, 'How does the chapter''s structure — opening with a covenant violated by Saul and closing with giants defeated by David''s men — serve the theological arc of 1-2 Samuel?', 'It shows that the consequences of Saul''s unfaithfulness (famine, covenant breach) are being resolved under David, while David''s own vulnerability (he nearly died) is covered by loyal servants, pointing to God''s grace sustaining the Davidic line', 'It is primarily an appendix with no theological connection to the main narrative', 'It shows that David had fully atoned for all previous sins in this chapter', 'It demonstrates that military victories alone guarantee divine blessing for a dynasty', 'a', 'Chapter 21 pairs the resolution of Saul''s blood guilt (atonement by execution and burial, 21:1-14) with David''s preserved life (Abishai saves him, 21:17) and his servants'' victories over giants (21:18-22), showing covenant faithfulness (David to Jonathan) and God''s protection of the Davidic promise despite human frailty.');

-- ═══ 2 Samuel Chapter 22 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('2 Samuel', 22, 'kids', 1, 'What did David call the LORD at the very beginning of his song of praise?', 'My rock, and my fortress, and my deliverer', 'My shepherd and my light', 'My king and my judge', 'My father and my helper', 'a', 'David spoke unto the LORD the words of this song...and he said, "The LORD is my rock, and my fortress, and my deliverer" (2 Samuel 22:1-2).'),
('2 Samuel', 22, 'kids', 2, 'What did David say about the LORD in verse 7 when he was in distress?', 'He said he cried to the LORD and the LORD heard his voice from his temple', 'He said he prayed in silence and the LORD answered in a dream', 'He said he called to his servants to pray for him', 'He said the LORD sent an angel to comfort him', 'a', 'David said, "In my distress I called upon the LORD...he did hear my voice out of his temple, and my cry did enter into his ears" (2 Samuel 22:7).'),
('2 Samuel', 22, 'kids', 3, 'What does David say the LORD rewards people for at the end of the psalm?', 'He rewards the merciful with mercy and the upright according to their uprightness', 'He rewards the richest people the most', 'He rewards only kings and priests', 'He rewards those who offer the most sacrifices', 'a', 'David said, "With the merciful thou wilt shew thyself merciful, and with the upright man thou wilt shew thyself upright" (2 Samuel 22:26).'),
-- Teens
('2 Samuel', 22, 'teens', 1, 'What dramatic imagery does David use to describe God coming to his rescue in the song?', 'The earth shook, smoke went out of God''s nostrils, fire devoured, he rode on a cherub and flew upon the wings of the wind', 'God appeared as a pillar of fire and led David through the wilderness', 'God sent a great flood that drowned David''s enemies', 'God appeared as a still small voice and spoke to David''s heart', 'a', 'David sang, "The earth shook and trembled...There went up a smoke out of his nostrils...He rode upon a cherub, and did fly: and he was seen upon the wings of the wind" (2 Samuel 22:8-11).'),
('2 Samuel', 22, 'teens', 2, 'What does David say about his own uprightness as the reason for God''s deliverance?', 'He says the LORD recompensed him according to his righteousness, because he kept the ways of the LORD and did not wickedly depart from his God', 'He says God saved him despite his many sins', 'He says he was delivered because he was king of Israel', 'He says God saved him because the people prayed for him', 'a', 'David sang, "The LORD rewarded me according to my righteousness; according to the cleanness of my hands hath he recompensed me. For I have kept the ways of the LORD, and have not wickedly departed from my God" (2 Samuel 22:21-22).'),
('2 Samuel', 22, 'teens', 3, 'What does David say about the lamp of salvation in this song?', 'He says the LORD will lighten his darkness and that by God he can run through a troop and leap over a wall', 'He says the LORD''s lamp will never go out in the temple', 'He says God''s word is a lamp to his feet on the battlefield', 'He says the LORD kindled a great fire of victory before his army', 'a', 'David sang, "For thou art my lamp, O LORD: and the LORD will lighten my darkness. For by thee I have run through a troop: by my God have I leaped over a wall" (2 Samuel 22:29-30).'),
('2 Samuel', 22, 'teens', 4, 'What military imagery does David use to describe God''s training of him for battle?', 'He says God teaches his hands to war and his fingers to fight, and that God''s right hand upholds him', 'He says God gave him a sword that never grew dull', 'He says God drove back the enemy host with arrows from heaven', 'He says God gave him wisdom to devise clever battle strategies', 'a', 'David sang, "He teacheth my hands to war; so that a bow of steel is broken by mine arms...thou hast also given me the shield of thy salvation: and thy gentleness hath made me great" (2 Samuel 22:35-36).'),
('2 Samuel', 22, 'teens', 5, 'What does David declare about the LORD''s way at the end of his great song?', '"As for God, his way is perfect: the word of the LORD is tried: he is a buckler to all them that trust in him"', '"The LORD is righteous in all his judgments and gracious in all his ways"', '"God alone is the fortress and none can stand against his might"', '"Happy is the nation whose God is the LORD, and the people he has chosen"', 'a', 'David sang, "As for God, his way is perfect; the word of the LORD is tried: he is a buckler to all them that trust in him" (2 Samuel 22:31).'),
-- Adults
('2 Samuel', 22, 'adults', 1, 'In what event context does the narrator say David sang this song?', 'In the day that the LORD had delivered him out of the hand of all his enemies, and out of the hand of Saul', 'After his sin with Bathsheba had been forgiven', 'After the death of Absalom and the suppression of all rebellion', 'On the night before the great battle with the Philistines', 'a', 'David spake unto the LORD the words of this song in the day that the LORD had delivered him out of the hand of all his enemies, and out of the hand of Saul (2 Samuel 22:1).'),
('2 Samuel', 22, 'adults', 2, 'What does David call God using six distinct metaphorical titles in verses 2-3?', 'Rock, fortress, deliverer, God, strength/shield, horn of salvation, and high tower', 'King, shepherd, judge, redeemer, saviour, and father', 'Light, fire, wind, rock, shield, and tower', 'LORD, God, Almighty, Most High, Everlasting, and Holy One', 'a', 'David said, "The LORD is my rock, and my fortress, and my deliverer; The God of my rock; in him will I trust: he is my shield, and the horn of my salvation, my high tower, and my refuge, my saviour" (2 Samuel 22:2-3).'),
('2 Samuel', 22, 'adults', 3, 'How does David describe the nature of God''s knowledge of and response to his distress in verse 7?', 'He says he called to the LORD in his distress and the LORD heard his voice from his temple and his cry entered God''s ears', 'He says God foreknew his distress and prepared a way of escape before he prayed', 'He says the LORD appeared to him in a vision before the battle to promise victory', 'He says God spoke through Nathan the prophet to comfort him in his hour of need', 'a', 'David sang, "In my distress I called upon the LORD, and cried to my God: and he did hear my voice out of his temple, and my cry did enter into his ears" (2 Samuel 22:7).'),
('2 Samuel', 22, 'adults', 4, 'What does David say God brought him into regarding his final state of deliverance?', '"He brought me forth also into a large place: he delivered me, because he delighted in me"', '"He brought me into the sanctuary and gave me rest from my enemies"', '"He placed me upon the throne and anointed me a second time before all Israel"', '"He brought me to the mountain of God and showed me his glory"', 'a', 'David sang, "He brought me forth also into a large place; he delivered me, because he delighted in me" (2 Samuel 22:20).'),
('2 Samuel', 22, 'adults', 5, 'What does David say about the froward (perverse) in God''s dealing with them?', '"With the froward thou wilt shew thyself unsavoury"', '"The froward shall be cut off from the land"', '"God turns away his face from the froward"', '"The froward shall not stand in the judgment"', 'a', 'David sang, "And with the froward thou wilt shew thyself unsavoury" (2 Samuel 22:27), meaning God deals with the perverse according to their own crooked nature.'),
('2 Samuel', 22, 'adults', 6, 'What does David''s declaration about his enemies in verses 38-43 emphasize about the completeness of his victory?', 'He consumed them, wounded them so they could not arise, beat them as small as the dust of the earth, stamped them as the mire of the street, and spread them abroad', 'He showed mercy to his enemies and offered them peace after victory', 'He took them as prisoners and put them to useful labor for the kingdom', 'He drove them out of the land and set border markers against their return', 'a', 'David sang, "I have pursued mine enemies, and destroyed them...I have wounded them that they could not arise...I did beat them as small as the dust of the earth, I did stamp them as the mire of the street, and did spread them abroad" (2 Samuel 22:38-43).'),
('2 Samuel', 22, 'adults', 7, 'How does chapter 22 relate to Psalm 18 in the Psalter?', 'The two texts are nearly identical, showing that this song was preserved in both the historical narrative and the Psalms collection, affirming its authenticity as a Davidic composition', 'Chapter 22 is a later summary of Psalm 18 composed by a court scribe', 'Psalm 18 is a shorter liturgical version while 2 Samuel 22 is the original battle hymn', 'The texts share only the opening verse and diverge completely afterward', 'a', '2 Samuel 22 and Psalm 18 are parallel texts with only minor variant readings, demonstrating that this was a genuine Davidic psalm that was incorporated into both the Samuel history and the Psalms collection.'),
('2 Samuel', 22, 'adults', 8, 'What messianic significance do commentators find in the closing verse of chapter 22 about David''s seed?', 'God shows mercy to David and to his seed for evermore, pointing forward to the eternal Davidic covenant and ultimately to Christ as David''s eternal heir', 'The closing verse applies only to David''s immediate physical descendants ruling in Judah', 'The promise of mercy to David''s seed was conditional on the seed keeping the law perfectly', 'The closing verse is a later addition added after the exile to comfort the returning captives', 'a', 'David sang, "He is the tower of salvation for his king: and sheweth mercy to his anointed, unto David, and to his seed for evermore" (2 Samuel 22:51), echoing the Davidic covenant of 2 Samuel 7:12-16 and ultimately pointing to Christ the Son of David (Matthew 1:1; Luke 1:32-33).');

-- ═══ 2 Samuel Chapter 23 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('2 Samuel', 23, 'kids', 1, 'What are the words called at the beginning of chapter 23?', 'The last words of David', 'The prayer of David', 'The song of Solomon', 'The testament of the king', 'a', 'Now these be the last words of David (2 Samuel 23:1).'),
('2 Samuel', 23, 'kids', 2, 'What did three of David''s mighty men do to bring him water from the well of Bethlehem?', 'They broke through the host of the Philistines and drew water out of the well of Bethlehem', 'They dug a new well near David''s camp', 'They carried water from the Jordan river for David', 'They prayed and water sprang up from the ground', 'a', 'Three mighty men brake through the host of the Philistines, and drew water out of the well of Bethlehem, that was by the gate, and took it, and brought it to David (2 Samuel 23:16).'),
('2 Samuel', 23, 'kids', 3, 'What did David do with the water the three mighty men brought him from Bethlehem?', 'He poured it out unto the LORD and would not drink it', 'He shared it with all his soldiers', 'He offered it to the wounded first', 'He drank it and praised God', 'a', 'David would not drink thereof, but poured it out unto the LORD (2 Samuel 23:16).'),
-- Teens
('2 Samuel', 23, 'teens', 1, 'What does David say a just ruler is like in his last words?', 'He that ruleth over men must be just, ruling in the fear of God, and he shall be as the light of the morning when the sun riseth, even a morning without clouds', 'He that ruleth over men shall be strong as an ox and swift as an eagle', 'A righteous king is like a strong tower to which the poor man runs', 'The just ruler shall be like a fruitful vine and his kingdom shall flourish', 'a', 'David said, "He that ruleth over men must be just, ruling in the fear of God. And he shall be as the light of the morning, when the sun riseth, even a morning without clouds" (2 Samuel 23:3-4).'),
('2 Samuel', 23, 'teens', 2, 'What was the exploit of Adino the Eznite, chief of the three mighty men?', 'He lifted up his spear against eight hundred, whom he slew at one time', 'He fought seven giants in a single battle', 'He held a mountain pass alone for three days', 'He defeated the Philistine commander in single combat', 'a', 'These be the names of the mighty men whom David had: The Tachmonite that sat in the seat...the same was Adino the Eznite: he lift up his spear against eight hundred, whom he slew at one time (2 Samuel 23:8).'),
('2 Samuel', 23, 'teens', 3, 'What did Eleazar the son of Dodo do in the great battle against the Philistines?', 'He arose and smote the Philistines until his hand was weary and his hand clave unto the sword, and the LORD wrought a great victory that day', 'He rallied the retreating troops and charged the Philistine line', 'He killed their commander and took his armor as a trophy', 'He alone held the city gate while David''s men regrouped', 'a', 'Eleazar arose, and smote the Philistines until his hand was weary, and his hand clave unto the sword: and the LORD wrought a great victory that day (2 Samuel 23:10).'),
('2 Samuel', 23, 'teens', 4, 'What did Shammah the son of Agee do in the lentil field while the rest of the people fled?', 'He stood in the midst of the ground, and defended it, and slew the Philistines: and the LORD wrought a great victory', 'He retreated to a hill and fought the Philistines in a narrow pass', 'He rallied the people and organized a counterattack', 'He single-handedly captured the Philistine commander', 'a', 'When the people fled from the Philistines, Shammah stood in the midst of the ground, and defended it, and slew the Philistines: and the LORD wrought a great victory (2 Samuel 23:11-12).'),
('2 Samuel', 23, 'teens', 5, 'Who was Benaiah the son of Jehoiada, and what were two of his famous deeds?', 'He slew two lionlike men of Moab, and went down and slew a lion in a pit on a snowy day, and also slew an Egyptian with the Egyptian''s own spear', 'He killed seven Philistine giants in the valley of Rephaim', 'He defended Jerusalem single-handedly when Absalom''s army first approached', 'He swam the flooded Jordan to deliver David''s message to Zadok the priest', 'a', 'Benaiah the son of Jehoiada slew two lionlike men of Moab: he went down also and slew a lion in the midst of a pit in time of snow: And he slew an Egyptian, a goodly man: and the Egyptian had a spear in his hand...and he plucked the spear out of the Egyptian''s hand, and slew him with his own spear (2 Samuel 23:20-21).'),
-- Adults
('2 Samuel', 23, 'adults', 1, 'How does David describe the inspiration of his last words?', '"The Spirit of the LORD spake by me, and his word was in my tongue"', '"The angel of the LORD appeared to me and gave me these words"', '"God spoke to me in a vision of the night"', '"I have written these words after many years of meditation on the law"', 'a', 'David said, "The Spirit of the LORD spake by me, and his word was in my tongue" (2 Samuel 23:2), asserting divine inspiration for his last oracle.'),
('2 Samuel', 23, 'adults', 2, 'What does David say about his everlasting covenant with God in his last words?', '"Although my house be not so with God; yet he hath made with me an everlasting covenant, ordered in all things, and sure"', '"God has confirmed my house will stand forever without any wavering"', '"My sons shall sit upon the throne of Israel for a thousand generations"', '"God has written my covenant on tablets of stone to endure forever"', 'a', 'David said, "Although my house be not so with God; yet he hath made with me an everlasting covenant, ordered in all things, and sure: for this is all my salvation, and all my desire" (2 Samuel 23:5).'),
('2 Samuel', 23, 'adults', 3, 'What does David compare the sons of Belial to in his final oracle?', '"The sons of Belial shall be all of them as thorns thrust away, because they cannot be taken with hands"', '"The wicked are like chaff that the wind drives away"', '"The ungodly are as the waves of the sea casting up mire"', '"Those who reject God are like a broken bow that fails in battle"', 'a', 'David said, "But the sons of Belial shall be all of them as thorns thrust away, because they cannot be taken with hands: But the man that shall touch them must be fenced with iron and the staff of a spear" (2 Samuel 23:6-7).'),
('2 Samuel', 23, 'adults', 4, 'How does the text describe what the people did after Eleazar''s great stand — what was the nature of the victory?', 'The people returned after Eleazar only to spoil the dead — they did not share the fighting, only the aftermath', 'The people rallied and together finished the routing of the Philistines', 'The people carried Eleazar from the field because he was so exhausted', 'The people offered sacrifices at the site of the battle in gratitude', 'a', 'The people returned after him only to spoil (2 Samuel 23:10) — they had fled and came back only to loot the bodies after Eleazar had won the battle alone, highlighting the singular nature of his heroism.'),
('2 Samuel', 23, 'adults', 5, 'Why did David refuse to drink the water the three mighty men brought from Bethlehem?', 'He said, "Is not this the blood of the men that went in jeopardy of their lives?" — treating it as sacred because of the life-risk involved', 'He said it was a sin to drink water fetched from enemy territory', 'He said the LORD had told him in a vision not to drink it', 'He gave it to the priests to pour out as a libation offering', 'a', 'David said, "Is not this the blood of the men that went in jeopardy of their lives?" therefore he would not drink it. These things did these three mighty men (2 Samuel 23:17).'),
('2 Samuel', 23, 'adults', 6, 'How did the rank and achievements of Benaiah compare to the chief three mighty men?', 'He was more honourable than the thirty, but he attained not to the first three, and David set him over his guard', 'He was equal to the three chiefs and considered the fourth greatest warrior', 'He surpassed all three chiefs in personal combat but was ranked lower by David', 'He was the most famous of all David''s warriors and considered greatest of all', 'a', 'Benaiah was more honourable than the thirty, but he attained not to the first three. And David set him over his guard (2 Samuel 23:23).'),
('2 Samuel', 23, 'adults', 7, 'Who is listed last among the thirty mighty men, and what is theologically significant about his inclusion?', 'Uriah the Hittite is last in the list, and his inclusion is a silent indictment of David — the king had him killed to cover adultery with his wife Bathsheba', 'Mephibosheth is last, honoring Jonathan''s memory through his son', 'Joab is listed last because he was the most loyal of all', 'Ittai the Gittite is last because he was a foreigner who earned his place', 'a', 'The list ends, "Uriah the Hittite: thirty and seven in all" (2 Samuel 23:39). Placing Uriah, whose murder David had arranged (2 Samuel 11:15), last in the list of David''s greatest warriors serves as a literary reminder of David''s gravest sin against one of his most faithful men.'),
('2 Samuel', 23, 'adults', 8, 'What does the phrase "ordered in all things, and sure" in David''s description of the everlasting covenant indicate theologically?', 'The covenant is both reliable in its terms (ordered) and unbreakable in its guarantee (sure), reflecting the unconditional Davidic covenant of 2 Samuel 7 that ultimately points to Christ', 'It means the covenant included detailed legal stipulations that both parties had to observe', 'It reflects the administrative organization of David''s kingdom under God''s law', 'It indicates David personally reviewed and approved every clause of the covenant', 'a', '"Ordered in all things, and sure" (2 Samuel 23:5) describes the Davidic covenant as comprehensive and unalterable, echoing 2 Samuel 7:16 ("thy throne shall be established for ever") and pointing forward to Christ of whom Gabriel said, "The LORD God shall give unto him the throne of his father David...and of his kingdom there shall be no end" (Luke 1:32-33).');

-- ═══ 2 Samuel Chapter 24 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('2 Samuel', 24, 'kids', 1, 'What sin did David commit that brought a plague on Israel?', 'He numbered the people of Israel and Judah', 'He worshipped an idol', 'He refused to offer a sacrifice', 'He took gold from the temple', 'a', 'David said to Joab, "Go now through all the tribes of Israel...and number ye the people." And David''s heart smote him after that he had numbered the people (2 Samuel 24:2, 10).'),
('2 Samuel', 24, 'kids', 2, 'How many people died in the plague that came as punishment for David''s census?', 'Seventy thousand men', 'Seven hundred thousand men', 'Fifty thousand men', 'Ten thousand men', 'a', 'So the LORD sent a pestilence upon Israel...and there died of the people from Dan even to Beersheba seventy thousand men (2 Samuel 24:15).'),
('2 Samuel', 24, 'kids', 3, 'What did David buy from Araunah the Jebusite to stop the plague?', 'The threshingfloor, to build an altar unto the LORD', 'A field for the people to hide in', 'A cave to place the ark of the LORD', 'An ox for the temple priests', 'a', 'David bought the threshingfloor and the oxen for fifty shekels of silver. And David built there an altar unto the LORD, and offered burnt offerings and peace offerings. So the LORD was intreated for the land, and the plague was stayed from Israel (2 Samuel 24:24-25).'),
-- Teens
('2 Samuel', 24, 'teens', 1, 'What were the three choices of punishment God offered David through Gad the seer?', 'Seven years of famine, three months fleeing before enemies, or three days of pestilence', 'Three years of famine, seven months of war, or one month of plague', 'Ten years of drought, one year of war, or seven days of plague', 'Forty years of wandering, seven years of enemies, or one day of the LORD''s judgment', 'a', 'Gad offered David three choices: seven years of famine, three months fleeing before enemies, or three days of pestilence in the land (2 Samuel 24:13).'),
('2 Samuel', 24, 'teens', 2, 'What did David say when choosing between the three punishments?', '"Let us fall now into the hand of the LORD; for his mercies are great: and let me not fall into the hand of man"', '"Choose the famine so the army will be preserved to fight our enemies"', '"Let three months of war be the judgment for I trust in my soldiers"', '"Let God decide without my choosing, for all three are too great to bear"', 'a', 'David said unto Gad, "I am in a great strait: let us fall now into the hand of the LORD; for his mercies are great: and let me not fall into the hand of man" (2 Samuel 24:14).'),
('2 Samuel', 24, 'teens', 3, 'What did David see that moved him greatly when the angel was stretching out his hand over Jerusalem?', 'He saw the angel of the LORD standing between the earth and heaven, having a drawn sword stretched out over Jerusalem', 'He saw a great fire descend from heaven on the city', 'He saw a pillar of cloud over the temple mount', 'He saw seventy thousand bodies fall to the ground at once', 'a', 'David lifted up his eyes, and saw the angel of the LORD stand between the earth and the heaven, having a drawn sword in his hand stretched out over Jerusalem (2 Samuel 24:16-17).'),
('2 Samuel', 24, 'teens', 4, 'What did David pray when he saw the angel and the people dying?', '"I have sinned, and I have done wickedly: but these sheep, what have they done? let thine hand, I pray thee, be against me, and against my father''s house"', '"LORD have mercy and spare Jerusalem for the sake of thy servant"', '"Remember thy covenant with Abraham and spare Israel thy people"', '"Let the angel pass over and let me bear the punishment alone"', 'a', 'David spake unto the LORD when he saw the angel that smote the people, and said, "Lo, I have sinned, and I have done wickedly: but these sheep, what have they done? let thine hand, I pray thee, be against me, and against my father''s house" (2 Samuel 24:17).'),
('2 Samuel', 24, 'teens', 5, 'What did Araunah offer to give David for free when the king came to buy the threshing floor?', 'The threshingfloor, the oxen for burnt offering, the threshing instruments and the oxen''s yokes for wood — all freely', 'Only the threshing floor itself as a gift', 'A portion of the land for a small payment', 'The oxen but not the threshing floor itself', 'a', 'Araunah said, "Let my lord the king take and offer up what seemeth good unto him: behold, here be oxen for burnt sacrifice, and threshing instruments and other instruments of the oxen for wood." All these things did Araunah...give unto the king (2 Samuel 24:22-23).'),
-- Adults
('2 Samuel', 24, 'adults', 1, 'Why was God angry against Israel at the beginning of chapter 24, and how does this make the narrative theologically complex?', 'The text says God''s anger moved David to number Israel, yet David is punished for it — showing divine sovereignty and human responsibility operating simultaneously in the same act', 'God was angry because David had failed to complete the building of the temple', 'God was angry at Israel''s idolatry which David then compounded with the census', 'God was angry because David had broken his covenant with Mephibosheth', 'a', '"And again the anger of the LORD was kindled against Israel, and he moved David against them to say, Go, number Israel and Judah" (2 Samuel 24:1); yet David is then held responsible (24:10) — a theological mystery that 1 Chronicles 21:1 clarifies by attributing the instigation to Satan, showing the interaction of divine permissive will and human sin.'),
('2 Samuel', 24, 'adults', 2, 'What was Joab''s objection to David''s census command?', 'Joab asked why the king delighted in such a thing and said it would be a cause of trespass to Israel', 'Joab said the army could not be spared from their posts to conduct a census', 'Joab said Moses had commanded no census be taken except by divine command', 'Joab said the people would revolt if forced to register for a census', 'a', 'Joab said to the king, "Now the LORD thy God add unto the people...but why doth my lord the king delight in this thing?" (2 Samuel 24:3), implying the census was an act of pride or distrust of God''s promise.'),
('2 Samuel', 24, 'adults', 3, 'What was the total count of Israel and Judah when the census was complete?', 'Eight hundred thousand valiant men in Israel and five hundred thousand men of Judah', 'One million men in Israel and three hundred thousand in Judah', 'Six hundred thousand in Israel and two hundred thousand in Judah', 'One million five hundred thousand in total across both kingdoms', 'a', 'The number of the people was in Israel eight hundred thousand valiant men that drew the sword; and the men of Judah were five hundred thousand men (2 Samuel 24:9).'),
('2 Samuel', 24, 'adults', 4, 'What was the theological sin in David''s census, according to the broader biblical context?', 'The census reflected pride in military strength and trust in numbers rather than in the LORD, violating the principle that Israel''s security rested on God alone and not on the size of its army', 'The census violated the Mosaic law requiring a half-shekel atonement payment for each man counted', 'The census was sinful because it was conducted in the seventh year which belonged to the LORD', 'David had not received a direct divine command to count, which was required before any census', 'a', 'David''s own heart condemned him (2 Samuel 24:10); the census likely reflected trust in military numbers rather than God. Exodus 30:12 also required a ransom payment for each counted man "that there be no plague among them," which David apparently failed to observe.'),
('2 Samuel', 24, 'adults', 5, 'Where was the destroying angel when God commanded him to hold his hand, and what is the theological significance of that location?', 'The angel was by the threshingfloor of Araunah the Jebusite on Mount Moriah — the future site of the temple — and this divine arrest at that location consecrated the site for the permanent sanctuary', 'The angel stood at the gates of Jerusalem and turned back at David''s prayer', 'The angel halted at the Jordan River when David offered sacrifice', 'The angel was restrained at the border of Judah and Benjamin by a heavenly command', 'a', 'The angel was by the threshingfloor of Araunah the Jebusite (2 Samuel 24:16); the LORD commanded him to hold his hand there, and David purchased the site and built an altar (24:18-25); 2 Chronicles 3:1 identifies this as Mount Moriah, the very site where Solomon later built the temple.'),
('2 Samuel', 24, 'adults', 6, 'Why did David refuse Araunah''s offer to give him the threshing floor and oxen for free?', 'He said he would not offer burnt offerings to the LORD which cost him nothing, and insisted on paying fifty shekels of silver for the threshing floor and oxen', 'He refused because the law required personal purchase for a sacrifice site', 'He refused because he wanted to honor Araunah with a greater sum', 'He refused because the land belonged originally to the tribe of Judah', 'a', 'David said to Araunah, "Nay; but I will surely buy it of thee at a price: neither will I offer burnt offerings unto the LORD my God of that which doth cost me nothing." So David bought the threshingfloor and the oxen for fifty shekels of silver (2 Samuel 24:24).'),
('2 Samuel', 24, 'adults', 7, 'How does the purchase of Araunah''s threshing floor parallel Abraham''s purchase of the cave of Machpelah?', 'Both involve a patriarch insisting on paying full price for sacred land from a Gentile owner rather than accepting it as a gift, establishing a permanent legal claim through purchase', 'Both sites were later destroyed by enemies of Israel and had to be repurchased', 'Both purchases were witnessed by the same number of elders under the same legal protocol', 'Both sites were on Mount Moriah and were consecrated in the same ceremony', 'a', 'Abraham refused Ephron''s offer to give him Machpelah for free and insisted on paying full price (Genesis 23:13); David refused Araunah''s offer and insisted on paying for the threshing floor (2 Samuel 24:24) — both establishing incontestable legal ownership of sacred sites through voluntary, witnessed purchase from Gentile owners.'),
('2 Samuel', 24, 'adults', 8, 'How does the ending of 2 Samuel — with the plague stayed through David''s sacrifice on the future temple site — serve as a theological bridge to 1 Kings and the building of the temple?', 'It shows that the site of the permanent temple was identified and consecrated through David''s intercessory sacrifice, and that the temple''s purpose was atonement — staying the judgment of God — even before Solomon built it', 'It shows that Solomon chose the temple site based on David''s military victories in that valley', 'It demonstrates that the plague proved Israel was finally united enough for a permanent sanctuary to be built', 'It shows that God chose the temple site to honor Araunah for his generosity toward David', 'a', 'God halted the destroying angel at the threshing floor of Araunah on Mount Moriah (2 Samuel 24:16); David purchased it and sacrificed there, and the plague was stayed (24:25). 1 Chronicles 22:1 records David declaring, "This is the house of the LORD God, and this is the altar of the burnt offering for Israel," directly connecting the atonement sacrifice of 2 Samuel 24 to the temple that Solomon would build on the same spot (2 Chronicles 3:1).');
